<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><B></B></P>
<P STYLE="font: 18pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt"><B>NXT 
ENERGY SOLUTIONS INC.</B></P>
<P STYLE="font: 10pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0">Notes to the 
Consolidated Financial Statements</P>
<P STYLE="font: 10pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0">As at and for 
the three and six month periods ended June 30, 2016</P>
<P STYLE="font: 10pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0; border-bottom: 
Black 1pt solid">(Unaudited - expressed in Canadian dollars unless otherwise
stated)&#9;</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><B>1. The Company</B></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">NXT Energy Solutions Inc. (the &quot;Company&quot;
or &quot;NXT&quot;) is a publicly traded company based in Calgary, Canada.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">NXT's proprietary Stress Field Detection
(&quot;SFD&reg;&quot;) technology is an airborne survey system that is used in 
the oil and natural gas exploration industry to
identify areas with hydrocarbon reservoir potential.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">Prior to 2015, NXT&rsquo;s financial
statements reflected disclosure related to the use of &ldquo;going 
concern&rdquo; basis of presentation. Significant progress was
made in 2015 in expanding the business, which resulted in a significant 
expansion of the Company&rsquo;s liquidity and working
capital.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">Management determined that in preparing
these financial statements as at June 30<SUP>th</SUP>, 2016, there is no 
material uncertainty that may cast a significant doubt
on the Company&rsquo;s ability to continue as a going concern for the next 12 
months and beyond. However, NXT&rsquo;s financial
results are currently dependent on a limited number of client projects, and its 
longer term ability to continue as a going concern
remains dependent upon the ability to continue to attract new client projects 
and expand its revenue base. The timing of new client
projects remains uncertain.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 20pt 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><B>2. Significant Accounting Policies</B></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><B>Basis of presentation</B></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">These interim unaudited consolidated
financial statements have been prepared by management in accordance with 
generally accepted accounting principles of the United
States of America (&quot;US GAAP&quot;) and by applying the same accounting 
policies and methods as used in preparing the consolidated
financial statements for the fiscal year ended December 31, 2015.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><B>Future Accounting Policy Changes</B></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0; text-align: 
justify"><U>Revenue recognition</U>:</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">In May 2014, the US Financial Accounting
Standards Board (&ldquo;FASB&rdquo;) issued new guidance on accounting for 
&ldquo;Revenue from Contracts with Customers&rdquo;,
which supersedes the current revenue recognition requirements and most industry-
specific guidance. This new guidance will require
that an entity recognize revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or 
services to customers in an amount that reflects the
consideration to which the Company expects to be entitled in exchange for those 
goods or services.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">This new guidance will be effective
from January 1, 2018, and early application is not permitted. There will be two 
methods in which the amendment can be applied:
(1) retrospectively to each prior reporting period (which will include 
NXT&rsquo;s fiscal years 2015 and 2016) presented, or (2)
retrospectively with the cumulative effect recognized at the date of initial 
application. NXT is evaluating the impact of the adoption
of this new guidance and has not yet determined the effect on its consolidated 
financial statements.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0; text-align: 
justify"><U>Leases:</U></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0; text-align: 
justify">In February 2016, the FASB issued new guidance
on leases. The new guidance requires lessees to<FONT STYLE="font-family: 
FrutigerLT-Light,sans-serif"> </FONT>recognize most leases,
including operating leases, on the balance sheet as lease assets and lease 
liabilities. In addition, lessees may be required
to reassess assumptions associated with existing leases as well as to provide 
expanded qualitative and quantitative disclosures.
The new guidance is effective January 1, 2019. NXT is evaluating the impact of 
the adoption of this new guidance and has not yet
determined the effect on its consolidated financial statements.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 20pt 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><B>5. Stock options</B></P>

align: justify">The following is a summary of stock
options which are outstanding as at June 30, 2016:</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 0 49.7pt; text-
align: justify"></P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica,

<TR STYLE="vertical-align: top">
    <TD STYLE="width: 41%; padding-right: 5.4pt; padding-left: 5.4pt; text-

    <TD STYLE="width: 22%; padding-right: 5.4pt; padding-left: 5.4pt; text-

<P STYLE="font: 18pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt"><B>NXT 
ENERGY SOLUTIONS INC.</B></P>
<P STYLE="font: 10pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0">Notes to the 
Consolidated Financial Statements</P>
<P STYLE="font: 10pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0">As at and for 
the three and six month periods ended June 30, 2016</P>
<P STYLE="font: 10pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0; border-bottom: 
Black 1pt solid">(Unaudited - expressed in Canadian dollars unless otherwise
stated)&#9;</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 4pt 0 0 13.7pt; 
text-align: justify; text-indent: -13.7pt"></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">Stock options granted generally expire,
if unexercised, five years from the date granted and entitlement to exercise 
them generally vests at a rate of one-third at the
end of each of the first three years following the date of grant.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">Stock based compensation expense (&ldquo;SBCE&rdquo;)
is calculated based on the fair value attributed to grants of stock options 
using the Black-Scholes valuation model and utilizing
the following weighted average assumptions:</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 6pt; text-
align: justify"></P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" STYLE="width: 100%; font: 11pt Calibri, 
Helvetica, Sans-Serif; border-collapse: collapse">
<TR STYLE="vertical-align: top">
    <TD STYLE="width: 74%; border-bottom: Black 1pt solid; padding-right: 5.4pt;
padding-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 5.4pt"><B>Six months ended June 30</B></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 14%; border-bottom: Black 1pt solid; padding-right: 5.4pt;
padding-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 5.4pt; text-align: right"><B>2016</B></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 12%; border-bottom: Black 1pt solid; padding-right: 5.4pt;
padding-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 5.4pt; text-align: 
right"><B>2015</B></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="vertical-align: top">
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5.4pt; padding-left: 5.4pt">Expected dividends 
paid per common share</TD>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5.4pt; padding-left: 5.4pt; text-align: 
right">Nil</TD>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5.4pt; padding-left: 5.4pt; text-align: 
right">Nil</TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="vertical-align: top">
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5.4pt; padding-left: 5.4pt">Expected life in 
years</TD>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5.4pt; padding-left: 5.4pt; text-align: 
right">5.0</TD>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5.4pt; padding-left: 5.4pt; text-align: 
right">5.0</TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="vertical-align: top">
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5.4pt; padding-left: 5.4pt">Expected volatility in
the price of common shares</TD>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5.4pt; padding-left: 5.4pt; text-align: right">90 
%</TD>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5.4pt; padding-left: 5.4pt; text-align: right">111
%</TD></TR>

<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 20pt 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><B>6. Financial instruments</B></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">1) Non-derivative financial instruments:</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">The Company's non-derivative financial
instruments consist of cash and cash equivalents, short-term investments, 
accounts receivable, and accounts payables and accrued
liabilities. The carrying value of these financial instruments approximates 
their fair values due to their short terms to maturity.
NXT is not exposed to significant interest or credit risks arising from these 
financial instruments. NXT is exposed to foreign
exchange risk as a result of periodically holding foreign denominated financial 
instruments. Any unrealized foreign exchange gains
and losses arising on such holdings are reflected in earnings at the end of each
period.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 20pt 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">2) Derivative financial instruments:</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">As at June 30, 2016, there were no
outstanding financial derivative instruments.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 18pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt"><B>NXT 
ENERGY SOLUTIONS INC.</B></P>
<P STYLE="font: 10pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0">Notes to the 
Consolidated Financial Statements</P>
<P STYLE="font: 10pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0">As at and for 
the three and six month periods ended June 30, 2016</P>
<P STYLE="font: 10pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0; border-bottom: 
Black 1pt solid">(Unaudited - expressed in Canadian dollars unless otherwise
stated)&#9;</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><B>9. Geographic information</B></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">NXT conducts all of its survey operations
from its head office in Canada, and occasionally maintains administrative 
offices in foreign locations such as Colombia (to mid-2014)
and currently Bolivia. NXT has no long term assets outside of Canada.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">In May 2015, NXT executed a contract
to conduct a US $13.4 million (US $12.9 million net of applicable local sales 
taxes owing) survey project with a new client in
Bolivia. This contract was completed and recognized in revenue in NXT&rsquo;s 
Q4-2015 period.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">A contract amendment for an additional
survey project valued at US $1.0 million (net of taxes) was finalized in 
October, 2015. The results for this project were delivered
to the client in January, 2016, and it is recognized as revenue in NXT&rsquo;s 
Q1-2016 period. Accordingly, deferred revenue as
at December 31, 2015 included US $0.5 million (net of taxes) which had been 
invoiced as a progress billing for this project.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">Revenues by geographic area were generated
solely in Bolivia in 2015 and 2016, and were derived almost entirely from a 
single client in each of the periods.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">Revenues for 2015 were derived solely
in Bolivia, from a single customer.</P>

align: justify"><B>10. Other related party transactions</B></P>

align: justify">One of the members of NXT&rsquo;s Board
of Directors is a partner in a law firm which provides legal advice to NXT. 
Legal fees (including costs related to share issuance)
incurred with this firm were as follows:</P>

<P STYLE="font: 14pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: center"><B>Management's Discussion and Analysis</B></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">The following management's discussion
and analysis (&quot;MD&amp;A&quot;) was prepared by management based on 
information available as at August 10th, 2016 and should
be reviewed in conjunction with the audited Consolidated Financial Statements 
for the year ended December 31, 2015 and the unaudited
consolidated financial statements as at and for the 3 and 6 month periods ended 
June 30<SUP>th</SUP>, 2016. This MD&amp;A covers
the unaudited 3 month (&quot;Q2-16&quot;) and 6 month year-to-date (&ldquo;2016 
YTD&rdquo;) periods ended June 30, 2016, with comparative
totals for the 3 month (&ldquo;Q2-15&rdquo;) and 6 month year-to-date 
(&ldquo;2015 YTD&rdquo;) periods ended June 30, 2015.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">As used in this MD&amp;A, the terms
&quot;we&quot;, &quot;us&quot;, &quot;our&quot;, &quot;NXT&quot; and the 
&quot;Company&quot; mean NXT Energy Solutions Inc.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">Our functional and reporting currency
is the Canadian dollar. All references to &quot;dollars&quot; in this MD&amp;A 
refer to Canadian or Cdn. dollars (&ldquo;Cdn $&rdquo;)
unless specific reference is made to United States or US dollars 
(&quot;US$&quot;).</P>

&ldquo;scheduled&rdquo;, and relate primarily to:</P>

<P STYLE="font: 12pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 20pt 0 10pt; text-
align: center"><B>Non GAAP measures</B></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">NXT's accompanying consolidated financial
statements are prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally 
accepted in the United States of America (&quot;US GAAP&quot;).&nbsp;
This MD&amp;A includes references to terms such as net working capital and net 
working capital before the undernoted items, terms
which do not have a standardized meaning prescribed by US GAAP and may not be 
comparable to similar measures presented by other
entities.&nbsp; Management of NXT uses this non-GAAP measure&nbsp;to improve its
ability to assess liquidity
at a point in time.&nbsp; Net working capital before the undernoted items is 
defined as total current assets less total current
liabilities, excluding amounts accumulated in work in progress and deferred 
revenue.&nbsp; Management excludes these amounts from
the calculation as they do not represent future cash inflows or outflows to the 
Company.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><B>Description of the Business</B></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">NXT provides an Airborne, gravity-based
geophysical survey to leading oil and gas Exploration and Production 
(&ldquo;E&amp;P&rdquo;) companies globally.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">NXT's proprietary patent pending Stress
Field Detection (&quot;SFD<SUP>&reg;</SUP>&quot;) survey method is used to 
identify subsurface trapped fluid accumulations by confirming
the existence of trap, reservoir and seal. &nbsp;Subtle changes in the earth's 
gravitational field caused by variations in sub-surface
geological density/stress patterns can be indicators of potential hydrocarbon 
accumulations. This is a critical piece of information
within the exploration process, only identified by the use of SFD&reg; 
technology and is crucial to the commercial success of exploration
projects. This is what makes the SFD<SUP>&reg;&nbsp;&nbsp; </SUP>technology so 
valuable to the industry.&nbsp; The SFD&reg; method
is used as an Executive Decision making tool designed to minimize risk and 
finding costs and maximize exploration program efficiencies
in terms of time and success rates.&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">SFD<SUP>&reg; </SUP>surveys are non-invasive,
environmentally friendly, unaffected by ground security concerns and effective 
in both offshore and onshore environments.&nbsp;
The results of the survey enable the customer to focus their exploration efforts
towards areas with a high success potential, thus
minimizing the huge expense of drilling non-commercial prospects.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">SFD<SUP>&reg;</SUP> is an established
exploration tool with a number of clients globally and a growing list of 
recommended prospects drilled with significant discoveries.
This tool is particularly useful as an early stage exploration tool in frontier 
and under-developed areas. SFD<SUP>&reg;</SUP>
is also used prior to drilling in areas that have significant seismic coverage 
to verify the presence of a reservoir and thus reduce
project risk.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">We have expanded our potential client
lists in the international markets such as South and Central America, Africa and
Asia and Middle East.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 20pt 0 10pt; text-
align: center"><B>Business Overview and Strategy</B></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">In 2016, NXT has increased its
investment in business development focusing on growing its pipeline of potential
clients to develop strong and reliable
projects that will help provide a balanced revenue flow going forward. This 
activity resulted in an increase in the
potential future revenue stream  despite the downturn in the industry.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">This improvement is due to the change
in marketing strategy that was implemented in 2015.&nbsp; Following the success 
of selling the SFD<SUP>&reg;</SUP> concept to independent
E&amp;P companies and the National Oil Companies (&ldquo;NOCs&rdquo;) for 
limited areas, we are now expanding our scope to cover
entire regions and countries. This new strategy focuses on working with heads of
government and senior executives who are not only
interested in the science but also in the economic benefits.&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">Following the successful completion
of the Bolivia Survey Project<FONT STYLE="color: #1F497D">s</FONT> in 2015, NXT 
has been effective in positioning the SFD<SUP>&reg;</SUP>
method as an established geophysical tool backed by technical papers, past 
project case studies, a strong list of references and
letters of recommendations.</P>
<!-- Field: Page; Sequence: 3; Value: 2 -->
    <DIV STYLE="margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; border-bottom: Black 1pt

Solutions Inc.</P><P STYLE="margin: 0">MD&amp;A for the Q2 period ended June 30,
2016</P></TD><TD STYLE="text-align: center; width: 29%">&nbsp;</TD><TD

    <DIV STYLE="page-break-before: always; margin-top: 6pt; margin-bottom:

    <!-- Field: /Page -->
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">The senior members of management undertook
an extensive marketing initiative in Q2 2016, which has resulted in building 
stronger relationships with global NOC&rsquo;s in
Africa, Asia Pacific, and the Middle East. Many of the potential clients in 
these regions are currently in various stages &ndash;
some quite advanced - of discussions with NXT.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">While we continue to grow the project
pipeline, our strategy will remain focused on National Oil Companies and 
integrating our services into their exploration processes.&nbsp;
We believe this approach will help us build a steady backlog of projects.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">As NXT pursues various international
markets, our strategy is to utilize high quality local sales representatives 
with&nbsp; key knowledge of their area, potential
clients and the exploration sector of the oil and gas industry.&nbsp; This 
allows us to cover larger areas and more clients with
minimum fixed cost.&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">NXT currently has sales representatives
to pursue SFD<SUP>&reg;</SUP> opportunities in such markets as Latin America, 
South Asia (Pakistan and India), Africa and the
Middle-East.&nbsp;&nbsp;All independent international sales representatives are 
required to certify that they adhere to NXT's
code of conduct and business ethics.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">It should be noted, however, that
the process of expanding the client base has ongoing challenges, due to such 
factors as:</P>
<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%" STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, 
Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 10pt"><TR STYLE="vertical-
align: top">
<TD STYLE="width: 0.25in"></TD><TD STYLE="width: 0.25in"><FONT STYLE="font-
family: Symbol">&#183;</FONT></TD><TD STYLE="text-align: justify">The 
exploration cycle is long in nature, and generating results from SFD<SUP>&reg; 
</SUP>recommendations
made in past surveys takes time and patience to realize.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 0 
0.5in">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%" STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri,

align: top">
<TD STYLE="width: 0.25in"></TD><TD STYLE="width: 0.25in"><FONT STYLE="font-
family: Symbol">&#183;</FONT></TD><TD STYLE="text-align: justify">Large NOCs 
tend to have a long decision making and approval process.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 0 
0.5in">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%" STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri,

<TD STYLE="width: 0.25in"></TD><TD STYLE="width: 0.25in"><FONT STYLE="font-
family: Symbol">&#183;</FONT></TD><TD STYLE="text-align: justify">The current, 
ongoing downturn in commodity prices in the oil and gas 
industry.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">The discussion in the MD&amp;A focuses
on the highlights of NXT&rsquo;s ongoing business development activities, and 
any significant changes arising subsequent to the
filing of our MD&amp;A for the fiscal year ended December 31, 2015.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">Estimates of the timing and securing
of future contract opportunities are forward-looking expectations which are 
dependent upon regional political and other factors
that are beyond NXT&rsquo;s control.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 20pt 0 10pt; text-
align: center"><B>Near-term Outlook for 2016 </B></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">There are a number of short term and
longer term prospects that are being pursued in South and Central America, the 
frontier areas of Africa, Asia, the Arctic and
offshore Atlantic regions (particularly where Canadian and American E&amp;P 
companies are operating).&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">NXT has been working with a number
of clients towards finalizing survey contract<FONT STYLE="color: 
#1F497D">s</FONT>, however the process within the NOC&rsquo;s
and related Government departments in these regions are complex and time 
consuming<FONT STYLE="color: #1F497D">.</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt/105% Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 8pt; text-
align: justify">NXT anticipates performing work
in the following countries in the near term:</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt/105% Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 8pt; text-
align: justify">Malaysia</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt/105% Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 8pt; text-
align: justify">Ghana</P>

<P STYLE="font: 11pt/105% Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 8pt; text-

method to help evaluate their prospects. We believe these organizations view 
SFD<SUP>&reg;</SUP> as an essential tool to achieve

<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-

<P STYLE="font: 12pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 20pt 0 10pt; text-
align: center"><B>Other Business</B></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0; text-align: 
justify">We have made significant progress in the development
of algorithms to model the SFD signal. We believe that this will enable NXT to 
create software to enhance and accelerate SFD data
interpretation as well as assisting clients in the understanding of SFD 
recommendations. The end goal will be for the client to
independently interpret SFD data.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0; text-align: 
justify">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0; text-align: 
justify">We have completed the testing of the upgraded
SFD Data Acquisition System. This system will be used on all future SFD survey 
projects. This system is more reliable, compact,
and expandable to acquire larger SFD datasets and eliminates the dependency on 
custom operating systems.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0; text-align: 
justify">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0; text-align:
justify">We have successfully defended all questions
raised to date by patent examiners regarding our patent application that was 
filed in May, 2012. We now await the outcome of their
deliberations.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0; text-align: 
justify">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0; text-align: 
justify">We are pleased to welcome Bev Stewart as our
new CFO. Bev is a CPA with over 20 years&rsquo; experience in senior financial 
roles within the international energy and oil and
gas industries. She was formerly Chief Financial Officer of TransCanada Turbines
Ltd (TCT), a joint venture company owned by TransCanada
Pipelines and Wood Group Plc.</P>

text-align: center"><B>Summary of Quarterly Results
(Unaudited)</B></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">A summary of operating results for
each of the trailing 8 quarters (including a comparison of certain key 
categories to each respective prior quarter) follows. The
extent of the profit or loss each quarter is mainly due to the timing and the 
number of SFD<SUP>&reg;</SUP> survey contracts that
have been completed or are underway, and variances in such non-cash items as 
stock based compensation expense (&quot;SBCE&quot;),
which can occasionally be a significant expense in any given quarter Also in Q3-
15, upon conversion of the outstanding preferred
shares, NXT recorded a significant intellectual property asset, which is being 
amortized (a non-cash expense) over a 15 year period.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><I><U>Q2-16 to Q1-16 comparison</U></I>
&ndash; NXT had survey revenue of $nil ($1,454,988 in Q1-16), survey costs 
(related to equipment test flights and aircraft maintenance
costs) of $157,365 ($789,379 in Q1-16), and SBCE of $135,000 ($150,000 in Q1-
16).</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><I><U>Q1-16 to Q4-15 comparison</U></I>
&ndash; NXT had survey revenue of $1,454,988 ($17,422,151 in Q4-15), survey 
costs, net of $789,379 ($5,070,023 in Q4-15), and SBCE
of $150,000 ($490,000 in Q4-15), amortization expense of $514,258 ($523,760 in 
Q4-15), and a total net income tax expense of $275,997
(a net income tax recovery of $5,415,933 in Q4-15).</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><I><U>Q4-15 to Q3-15 comparison</U></I>
&ndash; NXT had survey revenue of $17,422,151 ($nil in Q3-15), survey costs of 
$5,070,023 ($nil in Q3-15), SBCE of $490,000 ($169,000
in Q3-15), amortization expense of $523,760 ($146,828 in Q3-15), and a total net
income tax recovery of $5,415,933 (income tax
expense of $485,788 in Q3-15).</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><I><U>Q3-15 to Q2-15 comparison</U></I>
&ndash; NXT had survey revenue of $nil ($nil in Q2-15), survey costs of $nil 
($228 in Q2-15), SBCE of $169,000 ($228,000 in Q2-15),
and total amortization expense of $146,828 ($18,830 in Q2-15).</P>

<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 4pt 13.5pt; 
text-align: justify; text-indent: -13.5pt"></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 4pt 0 0 9.35pt; 
text-indent: -9.35pt"></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><I><U>SFD<SUP>&reg;</SUP> survey operations</U></I>
- NXT applies the completed contract basis of revenue recognition, with survey 
revenue and expenses recognized in the quarterly
period in which the overall survey recommendations report is delivered to our 
client and the obligation under the contract is fulfilled.
In 2015, NXT completed Bolivia survey projects totaling US $13.2 million. An 
additional expansion project that was flown for YPFB
was delivered and completed in January, 2016, which resulted in US $1 million 
(for which one half had been billed and received
to December 31, 2015) of revenue recognition in the Q1-16 period. The second 
half of the contract billing for this expansion project
was issued and received in Q1-16.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">Survey expenses in 2016 include the
net costs related to maintaining our survey aircraft, which was acquired in 
December 2015. The aircraft is available for charter
to third parties through our aircraft manager when it is not being used by 
NXT.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 6pt 0.75in; 
text-align: justify; text-indent: -0.25in"></P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, 
Sans-Serif; width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse">
<TR STYLE="vertical-align: top">
    <TD STYLE="width: 51%; border-bottom: Black 1pt solid; padding-right: 5.4pt;
padding-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 5.4pt"><B>Three month period ended June 
30th</B></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 12%; border-bottom: Black 1pt solid; padding-right: 5.4pt;
padding-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 5.4pt; text-align: right"><B>Q2-16</B></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 11%; border-bottom: Black 1pt solid; padding-right: 5.4pt;
padding-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 5.4pt; text-align: right"><B>Q2-15</B></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 14%; border-bottom: Black 1pt solid; padding-right: 5.4pt;

changes in G&amp;A within the five individual expense categories noted above
reflect several factors:</P>
<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%" STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri,

<TD STYLE="width: 0.25in"></TD><TD STYLE="width: 0.25in"><FONT STYLE="font-
family: Symbol">&#183;</FONT></TD><TD STYLE="text-align: justify">Termination 
costs and additional staffing levels contributed to the higher salary charges in
the
quarter.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%" STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, 
Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 4pt"><TR STYLE="vertical-
align: top">
<TD STYLE="width: 0.25in"></TD><TD STYLE="width: 0.25in"><FONT STYLE="font-
family: Symbol">&#183;</FONT></TD><TD STYLE="text-align: justify">Board, 
professional and legal fees, were higher in 2016 primarily due to investor 
relations activities
and additional costs legal and regulatory charges arising from moving onto the 
TSX from the TSX-V.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%" STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, 
Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 4pt"><TR STYLE="vertical-
align: top">
<TD STYLE="width: 0.25in"></TD><TD STYLE="width: 0.25in"><FONT STYLE="font-
family: Symbol">&#183;</FONT></TD><TD STYLE="text-align: justify">Business 
development costs were higher in Q2 following an extensive marketing trip that 
was undertaken
by senior management to some high prospect potential clients.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 0 13.7pt; text-
align: justify; text-indent: -13.7pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%" STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, 
Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0"><TR STYLE="vertical-
align: top">
<TD STYLE="width: 0"></TD><TD STYLE="width: 13.7pt"></TD><TD STYLE="text-align: 
justify"></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><I><U>Stock Based Compensation Expense
(&ldquo;SBCE&rdquo;)</U></I> - this expense varies in any given quarter or year,
as it is a function of several factors, such as
the number of stock options issued in the period, and the period of amortization
(based on the term of the contract and / or number
of years for full vesting of the options, which is normally 3 years) of the 
resultant expense. Also, SBCE is a function of periodic
changes in the inputs used in the Black-Scholes option valuation model, such as 
volatility in NXT's trailing share price.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">There was a higher average number of
options outstanding in the 2016 YTD period (total of 3,329,501 as at the end of 
Q2-16 as compared to 3,035,835 at the end of Q2-15).</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">SBCE also includes expense related
to the &ldquo;Rights&rdquo; which were issued in January 2014 (see discussion 
which follows in the &ldquo;convertible preferred
shares&rdquo; section herein) as follows:</P>

<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 4pt 49.7pt; 
text-align: justify; text-indent: -13.5pt"></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 4pt 0 0 49.5pt; 
text-indent: -9.2pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">In January 2014, NXT&rsquo;s CEO (the
&ldquo;Grantor&rdquo;) personally granted to various individuals 
&ldquo;Rights&rdquo; to acquire (at<FONT STYLE="font-family: Arial, Helvetica, 
Sans-Serif">
a fixed </FONT>price of $1.77 per common share) a total of 1,000,000 of the 
common shares which were expected to become issued
to him in 2015 upon the future conversion by NXT of the 8,000,000 convertible 
preferred shares he held.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">A total of 795,000 of these Rights
were granted in 2014 to certain NXT directors, officers, employees and 
consultants. In 2015, the initial 2-year term of all of
the Rights was extended by one additional year, such that the Rights expire on 
December 31, 2016.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">Even though these Rights are not an
obligation of NXT, but solely of the Grantor, under US GAAP they are viewed as 
an additional form of &ldquo;incentive&rdquo; issued
to certain of the holders, supplemental to NXT&rsquo;s existing stock option 
plan. This resulted in NXT recognizing additional
SBCE over the term of the &ldquo;vesting&rdquo; of the Rights, which was 
completed in 2015.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><I><U>Interest income, net</U></I>
&ndash; includes interest income earned on short-term investments. The total 
amount on deposit was slightly lower than 2015 levels.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><I><U>Loss (gain) on foreign exchange</U></I>
- this total is caused by changes in the relative exchange values of the US$ and
Cdn$. For example, when the Cdn$ trades higher
relative to the US$ , cash held in US$ will decline in value, and this decline 
will be reflected as a foreign exchange loss in
the period. NXT normally holds its cash and short-term investments in Cdn$ to 
reduce the effect of market volatility; however,
we periodically are contractually obligated to hold certain restricted cash 
funds in US$ instruments to support performance bond
commitments in certain foreign countries.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">The value of net US$ monetary assets
can vary widely each period, based on such factors as the extent of US$ revenue 
contracts in process, and the level of US$ cash
and short-term investments on hand.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">The valuation is also affected by the
relative strength of the US$ at each period end (which fell in 2016 as compared 
to the end of 2015 (1.290 Cdn$ / US$ at the end
of Q2-16 as compared to 1.37 Cdn$ / US$ as at Q4-15), resulting in both realized
and unrealized net exchange movements on the net
holdings of US$ cash and other working capital items.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><I><U>Intellectual Property and other
expenses</U></I> - this category includes primarily costs related to 
intellectual property filings and R&amp;D activity related
to the SFD<SUP>&reg;</SUP> technology, and costs for certain non-recurring, 
&ldquo;project&rdquo; activities</P>

<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">In Q1-16, other expense includes exchange
listing fees and related professional fees incurred to allow NXT to apply to

exchange, was approved effective March 22, 2016.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><I><U>Intellectual property and related
amortization expense</U></I> - NXT finalized its acquisition of specific rights
to utilize the proprietary SFD&reg; technology
from its inventor, NXT&rsquo;s President &amp; CEO, on August 31, 2015 with the 
conversion of the remaining 8,000,000 preferred
shares, on a 1 for 1 basis, into NXT common shares. NXT now has the exclusive 
ownership of and rights to utilize the SFD&reg; intellectual
property in global hydrocarbon exploration applications. After the conversion, 
NXT&rsquo;s CEO continues to retain the rights to
utilize SFD&reg; in other potential field-of-use applications.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">NXT&rsquo;s intellectual property (&ldquo;IP&rdquo;)
assets acquired in 2015 had a cost base of $25.3 million. The IP assets are 
being amortized on a straight line basis over a 15-year
period (future amortization expense of $1,685,000 per year), and will also be 
subject to ongoing tests of potential impairment
of the recorded net book value.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><I><U>Income tax expense</U></I> -
NXT periodically earns revenues while operating outside of Canada as a non-
resident within certain foreign jurisdictions, and services
rendered to clients in such countries may be subject to foreign with-holding 
taxes, which are only recoverable in certain limited
circumstances. Income tax expense for 2016 reflects such with-holding taxes 
which were incurred on charges related to the Bolivia
survey project.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: center"><B>Liquidity and Capital Resources</B></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">NXT's cash and cash equivalents plus
short-term investments at the end of Q2-16 was $5.0 million.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">Significant progress has been made
in the recent past in securing new revenue contracts and expanding our working 
capital. NXT's longer term success remains dependent
upon our ability to continue to attract new client projects and expand the 
revenue base to a level sufficient to far exceed G&amp;A
expenses, and generate excess net cash flow from operations. Equity financings 
have been used on a limited basis in recent years
to supplement working capital as required.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 11pt/115% Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 
10pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">Risks related to having sufficient
ongoing working capital to execute survey project contracts are mitigated 
through our normal practice of obtaining progress payments
from clients throughout the course of the projects, which often span 3 to 4 
months. In addition, where possible, risk of default
on client billings is mitigated through the use of export insurance programs 
offered via Export Development Canada (&ldquo;EDC&rdquo;).</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">EDC can also be utilized by NXT for
financial support in the form of guarantees of specific bank letters of credit 
required to be issued by NXT as performance guarantees
on international projects such as on our current Bolivia project. This aids in 
reducing restrictions on working capital that is
needed to initiate and undertake projects.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">NXT has no secured debt, and had total
&ldquo;net working capital&rdquo; of $4.2 million as at Q2-16 as follows:</P>

<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 0 0.5in; text-
align: justify; text-indent: -0.25in"></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 4pt 0 0 0.5in; 
text-align: justify; text-indent: -0.25in; color: red">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">The $3.2 million year to date decrease
in net working capital is primarily due to the net loss incurred in the period, 
excluding the non cash charges of $1.3m.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">NXT applies the &quot;completed contract&quot;
method of revenue recognition - revenues and related project costs are deferred 
until the period in which the survey contract is
completed. At each period end, if applicable, deferred revenue (a current 
liability) represents progress billing amounts that are
to be recognized in revenue in future periods. Similarly, work-in-progress 
(&quot;WIP&quot;, a current asset) relates to deferred
survey costs which will be expensed in future periods upon completion of the 
related contracts. As these amounts do not represent
future cash inflows or outflows to the Company, they are excluded (in periods in
which applicable) from NXT&rsquo;s analysis of
net working capital. There were no amounts recorded in WIP and deferred revenue 
at June 30, 2016, while the totals at December
31, 2015 relate to the Bolivia survey project which was underway.</P>

the only financing activity was related to proceeds from exercise of NXT stock 
options ($95,566). No equity financings occurred.
Q2-16 reflects an $8,468 cash use for repayments of the capital lease obligation
and $145,444 proceeds from the exercise of NXT
stock options.</P>

of Directors is a partner in a law firm which provides legal advice to NXT. 
Legal fees (including costs related to share issuance)
incurred with this firm were as follows:</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 0 9.35pt; text-
align: justify; text-indent: -9.35pt"></P>

<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 0 9.35pt; text-
align: justify; text-indent: -9.35pt"></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 0 9.35pt; text-
align: justify; text-indent: -9.35pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">Accounts payable and accrued liabilities
includes a total of $19,843 ($62,048 as at December 31, 2015) payable to this 
law firm.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">In addition, accounts payable and accrued
liabilities includes $14,620 ($34,881 as at December 31, 2015) related to re-
imbursement of expenses owing to persons who are Officers
of NXT.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 20pt 0 10pt; text-
align: center"><B>Critical Accounting Estimates</B></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">The key elements and assumptions are
substantially unchanged from those described in NXT's annual audited 
consolidated financial statements as at and for the year ended
December 31, 2014. The following is also important to note:</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><U>Revenue Recognition </U></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">Revenue earned on SFD<SUP>&reg;</SUP>
survey contracts (net of any related foreign sales taxes) is recognized on a 
completed contract basis. This method of revenue recognition
is currently deemed as appropriate given the complex nature of the end product 
that is delivered to the client - while the quantity
of data acquisition can be measured based on actual line kilometers flown, the 
acquired SFD<SUP>&reg;</SUP> data does not realize
its full value until it is processed, interpreted in detail, and a 
recommendations report is generated and reviewed with the client's
geological and geophysical staff.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">All funds received or invoiced in advance
of completion of the contract are reflected as unearned revenue and classified 
as a current liability on our balance sheet. All
survey expenditures and obligations related to uncompleted SFD<SUP>&reg;</SUP> 
survey contracts (including directly related sales
commissions) are reflected as work-in-progress and classified as a current asset
on our balance sheet. Upon completion of the related
contract, unearned revenue and the work-in-progress is moved as appropriate to 
the statement of earnings (loss) as either revenue
or survey cost. Survey costs do not include any salaries and overhead related to
SFD<SUP>&reg;</SUP> data interpretation staff
(which is included in G&amp;A expense) or amortization of property and equipment
expense.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 20pt 0 10pt; text-
align: center"><B>Changes in Accounting Policies
Including Initial Adoption</B></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">The factors are substantially unchanged;
refer to NXT&rsquo;s annual MD&amp;A as at and for the year ended December 31, 
2015.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><I><U>Future Accounting Policy Changes
&ndash; Revenue recognition</U></I></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">In May 2014, the US Financial Accounting
Standards Board (&ldquo;FASB&rdquo;) issued new guidance on accounting for 
&ldquo;Revenue from Contracts with Customers&rdquo;,
which supersedes the current revenue recognition requirements and most industry-
specific
guidance. This new guidance will require that an entity recognize revenue to 
depict the transfer of promised goods or services
to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration to which the Company 
expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods
or services. This new guidance will be effective from January 1, 2018, and early
application is not permitted. There will be two
methods in which the amendment can be applied: (1) retrospectively to each prior
reporting period (which will include NXT&rsquo;s
fiscal years 2015 and 2016) presented, or (2) retrospectively with the 
cumulative effect recognized at the date of initial application.
NXT is evaluating the effect of the future adoption of this new guidance, and 
has not yet determined the effect on its consolidated
financial statements, which currently reflect the completed contract method of 
revenue recognition.</P>

<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt FrutigerLT-Light,sans-serif...; margin: 0">In February 
2016, the FASB issued new guidance on leases. The
new guidance requires lessees to recognize most leases, including operating 
leases, on the balance sheet as lease assets and lease
liabilities. In addition, lessees may be required to reassess assumptions 
associated with existing leases as well as to provide
expanded qualitative and quantitative disclosures. The new guidance is effective
January 1, 2019. NXT is evaluating the impact
of the adoption of this new guidance and has not yet determined the effect on 
its consolidated financial statements.&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 20pt 0 10pt; text-
align: center"><B>Risk Factors</B></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">NXT is exposed to numerous business
related risks, some of which are unique to the nature of its operations. Many of
these risks cannot be readily controlled.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><I><U>Future Operations</U></I></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">NXT is still in the early stages of
realizing wide-spread commercialization of its SFD<SUP>&reg;</SUP> technology. 
Its ability to generate cash flow from operations
will depend on its ability to service its existing clients and develop new 
clients for its SFD<SUP>&reg;</SUP> services. Management
recognizes that the commercialization phase can last for several years, and that
it can have significant economic dependence on
a small number of clients, which can have a material effect on the Company's 
operating results and financial position.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">NXT anticipates that it will be able
to generate both net income and cash from operations in future years based on 
its current business model; however this outcome
cannot be predicted with certainty. The Company has a history of generating net 
losses and periodic shortages of working capital.
The Company's consolidated financial statements do not include any adjustments 
to amounts and classifications of assets and liabilities
that might be necessary should NXT be unable to generate sufficient revenues, 
net income and cash flow from operations in future
years in order to continue as a going concern.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><I><U>International operations</U></I></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">NXT conducts the majority of its operations
in foreign countries, some of which it has not operated in before. This exposes 
NXT to various risks related to stability of political
regimes, knowledge of the local customs, duties and other taxes, foreign 
currency and funds repatriation, the ability to access
the relevant local services, and potential delays in commencing the 
projects.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><I><U>Management and staff</U></I></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">NXT's success is currently largely
dependent on the performance of a limited group of senior management and staff. 
The loss of the services of any of these persons
could have an adverse effect on our business and prospects. There is
no assurance that NXT can maintain the services of our complement of management,
Directors, staff and other qualified personnel
that are required to operate and expand our business.</P>
<!-- Field: Page; Sequence: 15; Value: 2 -->
    <DIV STYLE="margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; border-bottom: Black 1pt

    <!-- Field: /Page -->
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><I><U>Reliance on specialized equipment,
and the protection of intellectual property</U></I></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">NXT currently has a limited number
of SFD<SUP>&reg;</SUP> survey sensors which are used in survey data acquisition 
operations. In addition, there is potential risk
that the equipment could become damaged or destroyed during operations, become 
obsolete, or that a third party might claim an interest
in our proprietary intellectual property. The costs of legal defense of our 
rights to the SFD<SUP>&reg;</SUP> technology could
be very expensive.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><I><U>Related party transactions</U></I></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">NXT may periodically enter into related
party transactions with its Officers and Directors. The most significant related
party transaction was the historical &quot;Technology
Transfer Agreement&quot; executed on December 31, 2006 between NXT and its CEO, 
President and Director whereby NXT issued 10,000,000
convertible preferred shares in exchange for the rights to utilize the 
SFD<SUP>&reg;</SUP> technology.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">As was noted previously, in January
2014, Rights were personally granted by the CEO to certain individuals to 
acquire up to 1,000,000 of the common shares that are
expected to become issued to him by December 31, 2015 upon future conversion of 
the outstanding 8,000,000 preferred shares.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">All related party transactions have
the potential to create conflicts of interest that may undermine the Board of 
Director's fiduciary responsibility to NXT shareholders.
NXT manages this risk of conflict of interest through maintenance of a strong 
independent Board of Directors. Six of the seven
current Directors are independent. All significant transactions between Officers
and or Directors of the Company are negotiated
on behalf of NXT and voted upon by the disinterested Directors to protect the 
best interests of all shareholders.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><I><U>Volatility in oil and natural
gas commodity prices may affect demand for our services</U></I></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">NXT's customer base is in the oil and
natural gas exploration industry, which is exposed to risks of volatility in oil
and natural gas commodity prices. As such, demand
for our services, and prospective revenues, may become adversely impacted by 
ongoing declines in oil and natural gas prices. The
impact of price changes on our ability to enter into SFD<SUP>&reg;</SUP> survey 
contracts cannot be readily determined. However,
in general, if commodity prices decline significantly, our opportunity to obtain
and execute SFD<SUP>&reg;</SUP> survey contracts
will also likely decline, at least in the short term.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><I><U>Foreign currency fluctuations</U></I></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">NXT currently bills its revenues in
US$ and occasionally local currencies (such as in Bolivia). We frequently hold 
cash in Cdn$ as well as in US$ and other foreign
currencies (such as in Bolivia and Colombia) and are thus exposed to foreign 
exchange risk due to foreign currency fluctuations.
Additionally, most of our operating expenses are incurred in Cdn$. We do not 
currently engage in currency hedging activities which
can be used to mitigate this risk.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">As NXT continues to expand into foreign
markets, it may become exposed to additional foreign currency fluctuation risks,
and currency hedging strategies will be utilized
where appropriate.</P>

    <DIV STYLE="margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; border-bottom: Black 1pt

    <!-- Field: /Page -->
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><I><U>Interest rate fluctuations</U></I></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">NXT periodically invests excess cash
in short-term investments which generally yield fixed interest rates. 
Accordingly, NXT faces some risk related to volatility in
interest rates, as interest income may be adversely affected by any material 
changes in interest rates.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 12pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 20pt 0 10pt; text-
align: center"><B>Disclosure Controls and Procedures
(&quot;DCP&quot;) and<BR>
Internal Controls over Financial Reporting (&quot;ICFR&quot;)</B></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Arial, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-align:
justify">NXT's Chief Executive Officer (&quot;CEO&quot;)
and Chief Financial Officer (&quot;CFO&quot;) (together, the &quot;Responsible 
Officers&quot;) are responsible for establishing
and maintaining DCP, or causing them to be designed under their supervision, for
NXT to provide reasonable assurance that material
information relating to the Company is made known to the Responsible Officers by
others within the organization, particularly during
the period in which the Company's quarterly and year-end consolidated financial 
statements and MD&amp;A are being prepared.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Arial, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-align:
justify">DCP and other procedures are designed
to ensure that information required to be disclosed in reports that are filed is
recorded, summarized and reported within the time
periods specified by the relevant security authority in either Canada or the
United States of America. DCP include controls and
procedures designed to ensure that information required to be disclosed in our 
reports is communicated to management, including
our Responsible Officers, to allow timely decisions regarding required 
disclosure.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Arial, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-align:
justify">The Company has established and maintains
ICFR using the criteria that were set forth by the Committee of Sponsoring 
Organizations of the Treadway Commission in Internal
Control &ndash; Integrated Framework (2013). The control framework was designed 
or caused to be designed under the supervision
of the Company&rsquo;s CEO and CFO to provide reasonable assurance regarding the
reliability of financial reporting and the preparation
of financial statements for external purposes in accordance with US GAAP. During
the 3-month period ended March 31, 2016, there
was no change in the Company's ICFR that has materially affected or is 
reasonably likely to materially affect our ICFR.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Arial, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-align:
justify">However, in an evaluation of the effectiveness
of the Company's DCP as defined under the rules adopted by the Canadian 
securities regulatory authorities and by the US SEC, the
Company&rsquo;s Responsible Officers concluded that there are material 
weaknesses in the Company&rsquo;s ICFR that have a direct
impact on the Company&rsquo;s DCP:</P>
<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%" STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, 
Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 10pt"><TR STYLE="vertical-
align: top">
<TD STYLE="width: 9.35pt"></TD><TD STYLE="width: 18pt"><FONT STYLE="font-family:
Symbol">&#183;</FONT></TD><TD STYLE="text-align: justify"><FONT STYLE="font-
family: Arial, Helvetica, Sans-Serif">due to the limited number of staff, it
is not feasible to achieve adequate segregation of incompatible duties. NXT 
mitigates this deficiency by adding management and
Audit Committee review procedures over the areas where inadequate segregation of
duties are of the greatest concern, and</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%" STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, 
Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 10pt"><TR STYLE="vertical-
align: top">
<TD STYLE="width: 9.35pt"></TD><TD STYLE="width: 18pt"><FONT STYLE="font-family:
Symbol">&#183;</FONT></TD><TD STYLE="text-align: justify"><FONT STYLE="font-
family: Arial, Helvetica, Sans-Serif">NXT does not have a sufficient level of
staff with specialized expertise to adequately conduct separate preparation and 
a subsequent independent review of certain complex
or highly judgmental accounting issues. These complex areas have included 
accounting for income taxes and equity related transactions.
NXT mitigates this deficiency by preparing financial statements with their best 
judgments and estimates of the complex accounting
matters and relies on reviews by management, external consultants and the Audit 
Committee for quality assurance.</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Arial, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-align:
justify">As NXT continues to expand our operations,
we seek to reduce these risks by adding additional staff resources and the use 
of out-sourced consultants as financial resources
permit.</P>

    <DIV STYLE="margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; border-bottom: Black 1pt

Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><TR><TD STYLE="text-align: left; width: 38%"><P
STYLE="font: 10pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0">NXT Energy 
Solutions Inc.</P><P STYLE="margin: 0">MD&amp;A for the Q2 period ended June 30,
2016</P></TD><TD STYLE="text-align: center; width: 29%">&nbsp;</TD><TD 
STYLE="text-align: right; width: 33%">page | <!-- Field: Sequence; Type: Arabic;
Name: PageNo -->17<!-- Field: /Sequence --></TD></TR></TABLE></DIV>
    <DIV STYLE="page-break-before: always; margin-top: 6pt; margin-bottom: 
12pt"><TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="width: 100%; font: 10pt 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><TR><TD STYLE="text-align: left; width: 
33%">&nbsp;</TD><TD STYLE="text-align: center; width: 34%">&nbsp;</TD><TD 
STYLE="text-align: right; width: 33%">&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></DIV>
    <!-- Field: /Page -->
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family: Arial, Helvetica, Sans-
Serif">Notwithstanding
NXT&rsquo;s efforts to mitigate the risks associated with the above mentioned 
deficiencies, the CEO and CFO concluded that the
Company's ICFR are not effective and as a result its DC</FONT>P are not 
effective as at June 30<FONT STYLE="font-family: Arial, Helvetica, Sans-Serif">,
2016. NXT reached this conclusion based upon their assessment that there is more
than a remote likelihood that its ICFR will not
prevent or detect material misstatements if they should exist in our 
consolidated financial statements.</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Arial, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-align:
justify">There are inherent limitations on the
ability of the Responsible Officers to design and implement DCP and ICFR on a 
cost effective basis, which may result in additional
risks to the quality, reliability, transparency and timeliness of interim and 
annual filings and other reports provided under securities
legislation.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Arial, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-align:
justify">It should be noted that a control system,
including the Company&rsquo;s DCP and ICFR procedures, no matter how well 
conceived, can provide only reasonable, but not absolute
assurance that the objectives of the control system will be met and it should 
not be expected that the DCP and ICFR will prevent
all errors or fraud.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 20pt 0 10pt; text-
align: center"><B>Additional Information</B></P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify">For additional information on NXT
Energy Solutions Inc. please consult our website at www.nxtenergy.com, or the 
SEDAR website at http://www.sedar.com.</P>
<P STYLE="font: 11pt Calibri, Helvetica, Sans-Serif; margin: 0 0 10pt; text-
align: justify"></P>
